\section{Introduction}
% Content
Hearing impairment is a widespread global health challenge that affects millions of individuals and significantly impacts their ability to interact safely and independently with their environment. According to the World Health Organization (WHO), over 430 million people worldwide experience disabling hearing loss, a number expected to increase in the coming decades\footnote{Deafness and hearing loss, Available: \url{https://www.who.int/news-room/fact-sheets/detail/deafness-and-hearing-loss}. Accessed on 25-01-2026.}. One of the most critical challenges faced by hearing-impaired individuals is the inability to perceive important environmental sounds such as alarms, approaching vehicles, or verbal warnings, which can lead to serious safety risks, and existing assistive technologies, including hearing aids and cochlear implants, primarily focus on amplifying sound signals. However, these solutions do not provide sufficient contextual understanding of the acoustic environment, nor do they offer information about the direction of sound sources. As a result, users may still struggle to interpret their surroundings, especially in complex or noisy environments.This work proposes a wearable assistive system that enhances situational awareness for hearing-impaired users by integrating three key capabilities: environmental sound recognition, sound source localization, and real-time speech-to-text transcription. The system utilizes a multi-microphone array and a lightweight embedded platform to process audio in real time and deliver feedback through web visualization. Through these tasks, the system transforms acoustic information into intuitive visual, enabling users to perceive, interpret, and respond to surrounding sounds and speech in real time, thereby improving their environmental awareness, communication effectiveness, and overall quality of life.
\section{Literature Review}
In this literature review we will summarize and critically analyze existing solutions under two subsections: Tasks and Platforms. Each subsection covers a specific aspect, such as sound recognition, sound source localization and emotion recognition for the Tasks subsection, and wearable devices and mobile platforms for the Platforms subsection.

\subsection{Tasks} 
To implement an assistive wearable device, the first step is knowing how the system works and the functions it performs. This includes sound recognition, which covers both speech and non-speech sounds, as well as sound source localization and emotion recognition. 

\subsubsection{Sound Recognition} 
Sound recognition is the process of detecting, analyzing, and classifying audio signals so that a system can understand and interpret different acoustic events in the environment. This function forms the core of assistive hearing technologies, enabling devices to differentiate between speech sounds, which carry linguistic meaning, and non-speech sounds, which include environmental cues such as alarms, traffic noise, and daily activity sounds. 

\paragraph{Speech Sounds\\} 
Most of the newest wearable devices for deaf and hearing-impaired people focus on converting human speech into text and vibration instead of amplifying the sound. Speech recognition was addressed in~\cite{Antonia2021} where a speech to tactile translation system was presented, enabling speech perception through vibration. Also in~\cite{Senaha2025}, speech recognition was performed and text was displayed on smart glasses. While some speech recognition systems were general and used publicly available libraries, others focused on detecting specific words~\cite{Adnan2021}, operated in a speaker-dependent context~\cite{Yaganoglu2021} or focused on children with hearing losses~\cite{Chandrashekar2025}.
This subsection summarizes different designs (smart glasses, and visual and vibration feedback systems) that all work accurately for speech sound recognition.

\paragraph{Non-Speech Sounds\\} 
Sounds other than speech have also been addressed in works such as~\cite{Karroum2025} where detection of relevant sounds like horns and alarms was performed, and~\cite{Tang2025} where other sounds like fire alarms, boiling water and knocking were addressed. Also, emergency sound detection was addressed in~\cite{Munasinghe2025} and~\cite{Tan2025}. These represent the leading state-of-the-art models in non-speech sound recognition within assistive-technology research. 

\subsubsection{Sound Source Localization}
Deaf and hearing-impaired individuals need assistive solutions that not only recognize sounds or speech but also localize the sound source. Unlike hearing humans, who use binaural cues (ITD and ILD)\cite{Grag2024} to estimate sound direction, severely impaired individuals may miss environmental context even with automatic translators. Hence, many assistive systems emphasize artificial sound localization to alert users to the direction of alarms, vehicles, speech, or sudden events. The work presented in~\cite{Tang2025} performed localization using a 4-microphone array, estimating the direction of arrival of the sound. Microphone arrays were also used in~\cite{Senaha2025}%,~\cite{Rathna2024}
and~\cite{Tan2025} for localization. 
Thus, the temporal development of the reviewed studies provides a comprehensive view of sound localization. The results indicate that more recent solutions do not necessarily guarantee improved performance; rather, the studies conclude that enhanced localization is primarily driven by more effective audio preprocessing methods. 

\subsubsection{Emotion Recognition} 
One of the newest features used in recent research papers is speech emotion recognition, which helps deaf users understand the emotional state of the speaker and interpret speech more effectively. In ~\cite{Wessam2021} the authors used a CNN model trained on datasets to predict emotions and display them as emojis on AR glasses, achieving about 71.3\% accuracy. In ~\cite{Gupta2025} the authors used a pre-trained model (wav2vec2-base-superb-er) to classify emotions from audio by selecting the highest probability. The results showed good accuracy. This subsection highlights the importance of emotion recognition in assistive systems.

\subsection{Platforms} 
Hearing-assistive technologies have been implemented across multiple platforms, most notably wearable and mobile systems—each tailored to meet different user needs and environments. This section reviews research projects by platform category to illustrate how each supports real-time sound perception and enhances user safety in distinct ways. 

\subsubsection{Wearable Devices} 
Wearable assistive technologies have emerged as practical and innovative solutions to support people with deafness or hearing impairments in perceiving environmental and speech-related audio information. 
Most of the work relied on wearable designs embedding the different components and functionalities with the aim of providing the tackled information in comfort and efficiency. In~\cite{Goyal2023}, a wearable system through which caregivers could send haptic signals was presented. Another system was presented in~\cite{Buhat}, consisting of a headband and a wristwatch for sound classification and multimodal alerts. Another device embedding smart glasses and microphones was presented in~\cite{Matsuo2024} and a glove-based system was shown in~\cite{Abhiram2024}. these reviewed wearable systems demonstrate progressive advancement toward translating acoustic information into accessible formats through tactile, visual, and intelligent processing technologies. 

\subsubsection{Mobile Platforms:} 
Instead of using wearable devices, some researchers proposed alternative designs such as robot systems. These alternatives aim to support deaf users without requiring them to wear or carry any additional equipment.  This includes different examples such as the ones shown in~\cite{Lee2021} and~\cite{Muyi2023}, robotic platforms inspired by hearing dogs, other robotic platforms~\cite{Tang2025} and mobile phone-based approaches~\cite{Fukui2022, Mahmud2023}. Additionally, social robotics~\cite{Youssef2021SocialRobot} have the potential to be used in this domain. This section shows the mobile and robot platforms that are used as assistive systems for deafness and hearing-impaired people.




