\section{DESIGN DEVELOPMENT}
This section presents the design development of the proposed assistive system for hearing-impaired users, covering the requirements, constraints, and selection criteria that guided the design process. It also details the high-level and low-level system specifications, including the hardware and software architecture.

\subsection{Proposed Design}
The proposed assistive system for hearing-impaired users is a wearable solution designed to enhance environmental awareness. It integrates a hardware–software architecture that performs three core tasks: speech-to-text (STT), sound recognition, and sound source localization. These functions enable real-time situational awareness through visual feedback.
\noindent
In designing the system, the requirements, constraints, and selection criteria were carefully considered.
\subsubsection{Requirements}  
The following requirements define what the project needs and can be divided into three main parts. 
\paragraph{Hardware} 
\begin{itemize}
\item Microphone array: the system uses a microphone array  to capture sounds from multiple directions. 
\item Processing unit: the system uses processing unit to execute operations on data and control system functions.  
\item Visual display: the system includes a display to show text or descriptions.  
\item Portable power source: the system requires a portable power source to allow the device to work anywhere with minimal energy consumption. 
\end{itemize}
\paragraph{Software} 
\begin{itemize}
\item Signal processing: used for analyzing input sounds and reducing noise. 
\item ML model classifiers: model to categorize the incoming audio into classes. 
\item Tool for speech recognition: tool to analyze speech and convert it to text.
\item Tool for sound source localization: a tool to determine the direction of a sound source.
\end{itemize}
\paragraph{Performance}
\begin{itemize}
\item High recognition accuracy: the device should work correctly and achieve high accuracy.  
\item Low response time: the device should respond with minimal delay. 
\item Reliable operation indoors and outdoors: the device should work correctly in both indoor and outdoor environments. 
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection{Constraints}
Constraints are the limitations that must be considered during device design; they represent boundaries that cannot be exceeded. 
\footnote{National Library of Medicine, Available: \url{https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37718832/}. Accessed on 1-05-2026.}.
\begin{itemize}
\item Performance constraint: the device must be able to operate even with noise levels up to 60 dB.  
\item Economic constraint: the total prototype should not exceed 400KD. 
\item Quality constraint: response time should be less than or equal to 2 seconds.
\item Range performance constraint: the device should detect sounds within a maximum distance of five meters from the user. 
\item Reliability constraint: the system's accuracy for detecting critical sounds must be at least 85\%.
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Criteria}
 Criteria refer to factors used to evaluate and compare the possible solutions. 
\begin{itemize}
\item Safety: ensures that the device operates without causing harm—no excessive heat or sharp edges, also guarantees that the system does not produce misleading or incorrect outputs that 
could put user at risk.
\item Accuracy for Sound recognition: the system’s ability to correctly classify environmental sounds (e.g., alarms, vehicles, speech). high accuracy is essential for reliability and user trust. 
\item Accuracy for Sound source Localization: higher accuracy improves user awareness. 
\item Real-time operation: the system must process audio and generate descriptions with minimal 
delay to ensure that users receive immediate information about their surroundings. 
\item Hardware complexity: based on the number of components used in the system  
\item Power efficiency: the ability of the system to operate for extended periods while minimizing energy consumption. 
\item User comfort: ensures that the device can be worn for long durations without discomfort. This includes weight and heat generation. 
\item Cost: the financial requirements to develop and manufacture the device, including components, sensors, processing units, power systems, and assembly.
\item Software complexity: based on the number of classes and functions used in the code. 
\end{itemize}
\noindent
All of these requirements, constraints, and criteria helped in selecting the most suitable solution for implementation in Graduation Project II and achieving effective results.



