\noindent
Audio is captured using the ReSpeaker 4-microphone array (16~kHz, 16-bit PCM, 4+1 channels) and split into two paths: Path~A for sound localization (four-channel array) and Path~B for speech-to-text (STT) and sound recognition (mono signal).
\noindent
Preprocessing is applied to both paths. Path~A is segmented into 16~ms frames, while Path~B uses 0.96-second frames to match model requirements.
\noindent
Three core tasks run in parallel:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Sound Localization (Path A):} Multi-modal features (GCC-PHAT, GCC Strength, IPD, Log-Mel) are extracted and passed to a GRU model with a 32-frame context window (512~ms), classifying direction into 24 azimuth angles (0°–345°).
    
    \item \textbf{Speech-to-Text (Path B):} Mono audio is processed using the Google STT API, producing real-time \texttt{transcript\_text} in Arabic and English.
    
    \item \textbf{Sound Recognition (Path B):} Log-Mel features are fed into YAMNet to produce \texttt{sound\_label} and \texttt{confidence\_score}.
\end{itemize}
\noindent
The outputs are fused and displayed via a web interface, showing sound labels, transcriptions, direction, and confidence levels, with vibration alerts for critical sounds. The system operates continuously for real-time assistive feedback.

