\section{PROJECT REALIZATION AND PERFORMANCE OPTIMIZATION}
This section presents the implementation of the proposed assistive system, focusing on its three core subsystems: sound source localization, sound recognition, and speech-to-text. It further describes the experimental procedures conducted to evaluate system performance, followed by a detailed analysis of the results. Based on these findings, a set of design and algorithmic optimizations are introduced to enhance accuracy, robustness, and real-time operation.

\subsection{Planned Implementation and Experiments}
This subsection details the planned implementation of each subsystem, including sound source localization, sound recognition, speech-to-text, and the user interface. It outlines the underlying methods, development tools, and experimental setups employed for initial design validation and performance assessment.

\label{sec:investigation}
\subsubsection{Sound Source Localization}

A specialized  sound source localization method was developed to reliably 
estimate the direction of sound sources around the user. The localization pipeline 
comprises three stages: (a) signal conditioning and multi-modal feature 
extraction, (b) neural network-based directional classification, and 
(c) post-processing and direction refinement.

\paragraph{Audio Preprocessing and Feature Extraction\\}
Audio is segmented into non-overlapping 30 ms frames (480 samples at 16 kHz). For each frame, log-mel spectrograms are computed using a 1024-point FFT with a custom mel filterbank (40 bands, 0–8 kHz). No pre-emphasis or windowing is applied such that localization was conducted through CNN. Raw features are stored in CSV files. The training pipeline then applies:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Silence Removal:} Frames with RMS energy below 100 across at least one microphone are discarded, removing 8.1\% of silence while preserving 91.9\% of informative audio.Also for better performance, Silero VAD was applied with a threshold of 0.2. This filtering is applied uniformly to both training and test data.
    
    \item \textbf{Multi-Modal Feature Extraction:} A rich set of acoustic cues was computed from the microphone array: inter-channel phase difference (IPD; 3 dimensions), IPD-Mel features (120 dimensions from 40 bands across 3 microphone pairs), generalized cross-correlation phase transform time difference of arrival (GCC-PHAT TDOA; 6 dimensions), GCC strength (6 dimensions), GCC vectors (600 dimensions from 100 sample points across 6 pairs), and log-mel spectrograms (160 dimensions from 40 bands across 4 channels), yielding a 899-dimensional feature vector per audio frame.
    
    \item \textbf{Feature Normalization:} StandardScaler z-score normalization is fitted on the training feature set and applied to both training and test data:
    \begin{equation}
    \hat{x}_i = \frac{x_i - \mu}{\sigma}
    \end{equation}
    where $\mu$ and $\sigma$ are training data statistics, ensuring consistent feature scaling across datasets.
\end{itemize}

\paragraph{Localization Model Architecture\\}
A 1D convolutional neural network (CNN) was trained on the extracted features to implicitly learn the complex mapping between multi-microphone cues and source direction. The model comprises three convolutional layers with progressively increasing filters (32 $\to$ 64 $\to$ 128), each with kernel size 3, padding 1, batch normalization, ReLU activation, and dropout (rate = 0.2). The resulting feature maps are flattened and processed through two fully connected layers (256 and 64 units) with batch normalization, ReLU activation, and dropout (rates 0.4 and 0.3, respectively). The output layer produces 24 logits corresponding to azimuthal direction classes uniformly spaced across the full 360° around the user.

\paragraph{Training and Evaluation\\}

The model was trained using cross-entropy loss and the Adam optimizer (learning rate = 0.001, weight decay = 1e-4) with a StepLR scheduler that halved the learning rate every 20 epochs (gamma = 0.5). Early stopping with patience = 10 epochs on validation accuracy was employed to mitigate overfitting. Training employed 80\% of recordings for training and 20\% for validation; independent testing used a separate dataset collected under different conditions.
\paragraph{ Experimental investigation\\}
In this section, an experimental investigation of key parts of the presented design is presented. This covers the tasks of sound source localization, sound recognition, and speech to text. Although the sound source localization process has been developed by the authors, and the two other tasks are performed by existing work, all tasks have been tested in situations similar to the context of use with hearing impaired persons. 

\paragraph{Data Collection\\}
Data for sound source localization training and testing was collected in the setup shown in Figure~\ref{fig:E1-F} to include different source-receiver azimuth angles. 
The sound emitting loudspeaker was placed 1.75 meter away from the ReSpeaker microphone array. The speaker was moved according to each angle while the ReSpeaker remained fixed such that 24 angles around a full circle were covered: $0^\circ$, $15^\circ$, $30^\circ$, $\ldots$, $345^\circ$.  
There were two recordings per angle: the first 5 minutes used the same recording for all degrees (same speech for one person), and the second 3 minutes each degree had a position-specific recording. All the recordings were speech. The recordings taken from the ReSpeaker are raw WAV files. 
