\subsubsection{Sound Recognition}
The sound recognition subsystem was implemented as a core component of the proposed assistive system to enable real-time environmental sound classification for hearing-impaired users. The implementation was based on the pretrained YAMNet deep learning model, selected for its lightweight architecture, fast inference speed, and capability to classify more than 500 environmental sound categories.\newline

\noindent
The subsystem was developed in Python and executed on the Raspberry Pi 5 platform. Audio signals were captured using the ReSpeaker XVF3800 microphone array at a sampling rate of 16 kHz in 16-bit PCM format. A mono audio channel was used as the input stream for classification.\newline

\noindent
Incoming audio was segmented into 0.96-second frames, matching the required YAMNet input duration. Each segment was processed to generate log-Mel spectrogram features before being passed to the neural network model. For every segment, the model produced a predicted sound label and an associated confidence score.\newline

\noindent 
Planned experiments were designed to simulate realistic indoor daily-use scenarios. Testing was conducted in an enclosed room with approximate dimensions of \(6 \times 5 \times 2.8\) meters. Different sound categories were evaluated, including speech, silence, coughing, household object sounds, alarms, footsteps, and animal sounds. Both near-field and far-field sound sources were considered.\newline

\noindent
Performance evaluation focused on classification accuracy, confidence consistency, inference latency, and robustness under practical indoor conditions.

\subsubsection{Speech To Text}

Speech-to-Text (STT) subsystem was deployed as one of the major parts of the system to change spoken language into readable text in real time, to provide hearing-impaired users with the ability to access speech information more efficiently. The subsystem captures the audio input via the ReSpeaker microphone, then sends it to the Raspberry Pi 5 to process and convert it through the Google Speech-to-Text (Google STT) API.\newline

\noindent
Google STT is a speech recognition service based on the cloud computing platform and it is highly accurate in transcription and has low latency, thus can be used in real-time assistive applications. It was chosen among the various models because it is more reliable, responsive and has stable performance in case of constant use. Also, it supports many dialects, including the Kuwaiti dialect.\newline

\noindent
The subsystem helps in enhancing the usability of the subsystem in a variety of environments by supporting English and Arabic speech. But Arabic speech recognition poses even more issues because of the variations in pronunciation and dialect that were taken into consideration in the tests and evaluation.\newline

\noindent
This system was tested by using recorded sentences and words (such as podcast-style audio) as well as live speech from users in English, Arabic, and the Kuwaiti dialect. The audio was captured through the microphone, processed using Google STT, and the output was evaluated as correct, partially correct, or incorrect. After several tests, the accuracy is determined based on the output evaluation.\newline

\noindent
The audio input was recorded using a sampling rate of 16 kHz and one audio channel (mono), which is suitable for speech recognition. The real-time audio was divided into chunks with a duration of 1.2 seconds, with 0.3 seconds of overlap between each chunk. This reduced the chance of losing words between audio segments. Before being sent to Google STT for transcription, the recorded audio was converted into 16-bit audio format.\newline

\noindent
The output that is transcribed appears on a web-based user interface, which enables users to track conversations and spoken words in real time. The first design was to incorporate AR-based visualization but because of the hardware restriction and the cost factor, the present implementation is based on the web interface to achieve a practical implementation and testing.

\subsubsection{Interface Implementation}

The developed user interface provides clear, real-time, and accessible information to hearing-impaired users through a structured and intuitive visual layout. The interface presents three main components: sound recognition, sound source localization, and speech-to-text transcription.\newline

\noindent
Detected environmental sounds are displayed as prominent labels (e.g., \textit{Alarm}, \textit{Knock}) along with descriptive context to help users quickly understand the surrounding event. In Detailed Mode, additional confidence indicators are presented using progress bars to reflect prediction reliability, while in Light Mode only the most relevant sound label is shown to reduce visual complexity.\newline

\noindent
Sound source localization is visualized using a circular directional map combined with a pointer indicating the estimated direction. The output is presented both as an angle (in degrees) and as an intuitive directional label (e.g., Front, Right, Behind), ensuring precise yet user-friendly interpretation. This dual representation enhances situational awareness while keeping the interface easy to understand.\newline

\noindent
Speech-to-text output is continuously displayed in a dedicated section, showing live transcriptions of spoken sentences. Important or newly recognized words are visually highlighted to improve readability and user attention.\newline

\noindent
As shown in Figures~\ref{fig:ui_detailed} and \ref{fig:ui_light}, two operating modes were implemented to support different usage scenarios. Detailed Mode provides comprehensive information, including sound probabilities, directional visualization, and contextual details, making it suitable for maximum environmental awareness. In contrast, Light Mode presents only essential outputs such as the detected sound, direction, and speech caption, offering a simplified and distraction-free interface for everyday use.\newline

\noindent
Additional interface elements include real-time system status indicators (e.g., Live mode) and visual warning messages for critical events such as alarms, which are highlighted using distinct colors to ensure immediate user attention.

