\noindent
As shown in Figure~\ref{fig:sound_accuracy}, the subsystem achieves high real-time accuracy across different sound categories. Human speech achieved the highest performance with near-perfect accuracy, followed by alarms and animal sounds. Other sound classes such as tools and footsteps also demonstrated strong performance, with overall accuracy ranging between 88\% and 95\%.\newline

\noindent
The subsystem successfully classified a wide range of environmental sounds, including conversations, alarms, footsteps, object interactions, and animal sounds. Human speech was consistently detected with high confidence values ranging from 0.97 to 1.0, while silence was correctly identified with a confidence score of 1.0 in the absence of sound. Hierarchical recognition behavior was observed in some cases, where predictions were refined from general labels (e.g., animal) to more specific classes (e.g., cat, meow).\newline

\noindent
Performance analysis showed that recognition accuracy is influenced by several factors, including background noise, sound distance, and overlapping audio events. As the distance between the sound source and the microphone increases, signal attenuation and environmental effects reduce feature clarity, leading to lower confidence scores. For example, cough detection at approximately four meters resulted in reduced confidence due to acoustic attenuation and room conditions. Additionally, overlapping sounds introduce ambiguity in feature extraction, which may affect classification reliability.\newline

\noindent
The use of the pretrained YAMNet model enables robust generalization across a wide range of sound classes; however, minor misclassifications were observed between acoustically similar sounds. These cases typically occurred with low confidence values and did not significantly impact the system's primary objective of notifying users about important surrounding sounds. Confidence-based filtering can further improve reliability during real-time operation.\newline

\noindent
From a system perspective, the model provides low-latency inference suitable for real-time assistive applications. Detected sound events are presented with minimal delay, ensuring timely awareness and improved responsiveness, particularly for critical sounds such as alarms and warnings.


\subsubsection{Speech To Text}
The Speech-to-Text subsystem was tested in different test conditions to check its functionality, accuracy, and usability in various situations. Initially, when we wanted to choose the model to use for the project, we tried multiple speech recognition systems, such as Faster-Whisper and Google Speech-to-Text (Google STT). We compared the accuracy of transcription, response time, and stability of the system. Based on this comparison, Google STT was selected for the final implementation.\newline

\noindent
According to the experimental findings, Faster-Whisper was tested for Arabic language and Kuwaiti dialect under three different conditions: Kuwaiti dialect words and short phrases, adult vs. child voice, and noisy environment. The results showed that the system recognized the Kuwaiti dialect with some spelling variations. Words and short phrases were faster than full sentences. The response time for words and phrases was around 3.5 s, while short sentences took around 5.5–6 s. In noisy environments, the response time increased to around 6 s with slightly lower accuracy. For the English language, the results were better, although audio clarity significantly affected accuracy, and model performance depended on the environment. The response time was shorter than the Arabic version, and the errors were fewer.\newline

\noindent
The same test conditions were applied to Google STT. It was chosen to be implemented in the final system because of its better performance, especially in real-time processing. The response time in Arabic and English was very similar. Short sentences: ~2.3–2.5 s, medium sentences: ~4.5–5.8 s, and long sentences: ~7–9 s. However, it showed greater transcription accuracy and more reliable output compared to the other methods.\newline

\noindent
Arabic speech recognition was further complicated by dialects, pronunciation, and the phonetic similarity of some words. These difficulties sometimes led to slight mistakes in the transcription process, yet they did not greatly affect the general comprehension of the sentence. The design priority was to provide meaningful and understandable output rather than word-level accuracy.

\subsubsection{User Interface}

The user interface was evaluated based on usability, clarity, and real-time performance. The design prioritizes minimal cognitive load and rapid information perception by using clear labels, color-coded alerts, and simplified layouts. This allows hearing-impaired users to quickly interpret critical information such as alarms and sound direction without confusion or delay. In addition, the interface follows a clear visual hierarchy, where key elements such as alerts and directional indicators are emphasized to improve reaction time and accessibility. This design approach reduces user confusion and ensures that critical information can be interpreted instantly in real-time scenarios.\newline

\noindent
The two interface modes (Detailed and Light) were also evaluated in terms of usability and effectiveness. The Detailed Mode provides comprehensive information to support maximum situational awareness, while the Light Mode offers a simplified view that enhances readability and reduces visual complexity during everyday use.\newline

\noindent
Overall, the interface demonstrated stable real-time performance and effective communication of system outputs, making it suitable for continuous assistive operation.

