\subsection{Design Optimization and Improvements}
Following the initial system implementation, a series of design optimizations were introduced to address observed performance limitations and enhance overall system efficiency. These improvements were guided by experimental results and focused on refining accuracy, computational performance, and real-time operation across different system modules.
\subsubsection{Sound Source Localization}
Building on the observations from the previous section, the following improvements were applied to address two issues: the silent-frame detection failure traced to the Silero VAD module, and the latency imposed by the original 50\,ms frame size.

\paragraph{CNN Hyperparameter Tuning\\}
A systematic tuning study was conducted on the baseline CNN to improve its cross-recording (S2) performance while preserving real-time compatibility. The following modifications were evaluated:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Wider architecture:} The number of convolutional filters was progressively increased, and label smoothing was introduced to reduce overconfidence on training data.
    \item \textbf{Optimizer and class balancing:} The Adam optimizer was replaced with AdamW (weight decay = 1e-4), and balanced class weights were applied to the cross-entropy loss to mitigate any per-angle imbalance in the training data.
    \item \textbf{RMS threshold:} The silence-removal threshold was lowered from 100 to 50 to retain a greater proportion of low-energy speech frames.

\end{itemize} 


\paragraph{Frame Size — 16\,ms\\}
The frame size was fixed at 16\,ms (256 samples at 16\,kHz) to match the ReSpeaker XVF3800 processing chunk size, ensuring that features extracted during training correspond directly to the input received in real time. While larger frames improved offline S2 accuracy (Table~\ref{tab:frame_size}), they reduce temporal resolution and introduce buffering latency, making them incompatible with real-time deployment. In contrast, the 16\,ms frame preserves fine temporal detail and demonstrates better generalization to unseen acoustic conditions, and was therefore retained for all subsequent models.

\paragraph{VAD Replacement — RMS Energy Threshold\\}
The Silero VAD module was removed and replaced with a stateless RMS energy
threshold. A frame is accepted as speech if the maximum RMS amplitude across
the four microphone channels satisfies $\text{RMS} \geq 200$. Unlike the
recurrent VAD, this criterion carries no state between frames and cannot
become stuck during prolonged recording.

\paragraph{CNN — Sequential Overlap (seq\_len\,=\,2)\\}
The original CNN treated each frame independently (seq\_len\,=\,1). To
introduce minimal temporal context without fundamentally changing the
architecture, a two-frame sliding window (32\,ms total) was applied with
50\% overlap (stride\,=\,1). During training, a \texttt{SequenceDataset}
enforces that both frames in each window belong to the same angle and are
strictly consecutive. The flattened two-frame vector is passed to the same
CNN architecture. This modification increased offline cross-recording accuracy
significantly.

\paragraph{GRU — Long Temporal Context (seq\_len\,=\,32)\\}
A Gated Recurrent Unit (GRU) model was trained as an alternative architecture
with a 32-frame context window (512\,ms) and 50\% overlap (stride\,=\,16).
The architecture comprises an embedding layer
(Linear\,+\,LayerNorm\,+\,ReLU\,+\,Dropout), a single-layer GRU with 128
hidden units, and a classifier head. By learning temporal patterns across half
a second of audio.
 
\paragraph{Model Comparison\\}
Table~\ref{tab:frame_comparison} summarises the offline cross-recording (S2)
performance across all model variants.\newline

\noindent
Switching to a 16\,ms single-frame configuration (seq\_len\,=\,1) reduces
performance (76.34\%), highlighting the limitation of purely instantaneous
features. Introducing a two-frame sequence with 50\% overlap improves accuracy
to 83.04\%, indicating that even short temporal context enhances directional
estimation. The GRU, using a 32-frame temporal window, achieves the highest
performance by a wide margin, demonstrating the
critical role of long-range temporal modeling for sound source localization.

