\subsubsection{Sound Recognition}
Several improvements were introduced to enhance the reliability and usability of the sound recognition subsystem. Confidence-based filtering was applied so that low-confidence predictions were suppressed, reducing unnecessary false alerts. Priority handling was also introduced for critical sound classes such as alarms and loud noise events to ensure immediate user attention.\newline

\noindent
The recognition outputs were further synchronized with the speech-to-text subsystem to avoid conflicts between speech captions and environmental sound notifications. Additional practical sound categories, including loud noise events, were integrated into the displayed alerts to improve real-world usefulness.\newline

\noindent
To improve user interaction, sound recognition outputs were integrated with the updated visual interface, where detected sounds were clearly displayed together with sound direction, confidence indication, and live speech captions in real time.

\subsubsection{Speech To Text}
The Speech-to-Text subsystem performance was tested manually with over 60 case-tests in Arabic and English. These test cases had general conversations, frequently used phrases, and real-life communication situations to mimic real-life usage conditions, in addition to audio recordings such as conversations or podcast-style audio.\newline

\noindent
The ultimate analysis was done with the implementation of Google Speech-to-Text (Google STT) application. The system obtained a recognition rate of over 83\%, which is acceptable to real-time assistive systems. English speech recognition was found to be more reliable and quicker, whereas Arabic speech recognition had to be given extra attention as there were pronunciation and dialect differences.\newline

\noindent
Minor spelling errors were also noticed during testing, especially when it came to fast speech, unclear pronunciation, or words that were phonetically similar. These errors were minor and did not stop users from receiving the intended meaning of the sentence, although they somewhat influenced the overall accuracy. Also, if the conversation was long, the system skipped some words.\newline

\noindent
The subsystem as a whole was found to be reliable in its performance, and it met its goal of offering fast, easily comprehensible, and practical real-time transcription to help deaf and hearing-impaired users in their daily communication situations.\newline

\noindent
A few improvements were made to increase usability and system reliability. To initially assess the speed of the response, the chunk size was changed from 3 to 1.5. When the chunk size was 3 or 2, the accuracy was high, but the response time was long. When it was reduced to 1, it became fast, but the accuracy was low. Therefore, the selected chunk size was 1.2. This size combined response speed and accuracy. Then, it was noticed that in long sentences, the system skipped some words due to the chunk size. So, an overlap of 0.3 was added to make the conversion more accurate and reduce missing words. To make saving tests easier than manual evaluation, a Save Output button was added to save each test along with its output, duration, and the output rating selected by the user. A logging option was added to save the transcription results to be used later in the analysis. These improvements enhanced the subsystem to be more stable and easier to use in real time.

\subsubsection{User Interface}

Several improvements were applied to enhance the usability and clarity of the interface.
These include refining the layout for better readability, improving synchronization
between system outputs, and enhancing the visualization of sound direction using
both angular values and intuitive directional labels.\newline

\noindent
These optimizations improved user interaction, reduced visual clutter, and ensured
more effective real-time feedback.
