\subsection{Commercializing the Project and Relevance to Region (Social, Cultural and Political issues)}
The system, Scene Descriptor using Sound for Persons with Deafness or Hearing Impairments, has good commercial potential since it is a solution to a real and widespread problem of individuals with hearing problems. The system is developed in the form of a wearable cap with the use of microphones to record the sounds around, and the output is shown on a mobile device, i.e. a tablet or smartphone. This will render the system more convenient, lightweight and less expensive than other solutions, including smart glasses or AR-based devices.\newline

\noindent
The system mainly aims at people with hearing disabilities, both deaf and hard-of-hearing among various age groups. It can be used in different settings which include schools, universities, workplaces, hospitals, homes and in public places. The system allows users to identify key environmental sounds like sirens, alarms, car horns, doorbells, and speech warnings. Moreover, it translates speech into readable text and gives information on the direction of the source of sounds, which increases the level of user safety and responsiveness in everyday life.\newline

\noindent
Socially, the project enhances social inclusion and independence of individuals with hearing deficits. There are a lot of users who depend on other people to decode the sounds around them, particularly during emergency cases. This system minimises that dependency and boosts user confidence in navigating and communicating without relying on others. Visits to deaf and hard-of-hearing centers were also made during the development stage, which provided valuable insight into the actual user requirements and challenges. This helped to make the system more practical and relevant to the local community.\newline

\noindent
Culturally, there is a need to support the Arabic and Kuwaiti dialect. The available assistive technologies now are mostly in English, limiting their use by the local population. Local language support would be more acceptable to users in Kuwait and enhance acceptance of the system by the target population. This also enables the system to add value to the regional market.\newline

\noindent
Politically and regionally, the project helps Kuwait to digitalize and create assistive healthcare technologies. It helps to enhance access and equal opportunities of people with disabilities. Given that the project has an economic constraint, i.e. the overall system must not exceed 400 KD, the suggested solution is quite affordable in comparison to most of the existing assistive technologies. This will increase its chances of development and implementation by hospitals, rehabilitation facilities, educational programs and government programs in the future.. 
\subsection{Related Engineering Standards}
The suggested system is based on a number of engineering requirements that guarantee its safety, reliability, and effective operation. These standards are vital in real-life application since the system is a combination of hardware, software, audio processing and user interface.\newline

\noindent
To begin with, electrical safety must be noted as a very important aspect since the system will comprise components such as the Raspberry Pi 5, ReSpeaker microphone array, and a portable power source. Voltage regulation, safe wiring and secure power connections should be provided to avoid overheating, short circuits or destruction of the system. The device is worn and can be placed close to the body of the user; therefore, it is of particular importance to ensure electrical safety.\newline

\noindent
Second, it should take into account ergonomics since the system is developed as a wearable cap. The system must be lightweight, comfortable, and fit to be used on a long-term basis. The system weight should not exceed 500 grams because the project requirements state that the weight should be lowered to minimize strain and discomfort. Also, the heat production should be reduced to allow safe and comfortable continuous use.\newline

\noindent
Third, it should be easy to understand, which is one of the engineering requirements, given that the system will be deployed to deaf and hard-of-hearing users. The interface should be able to depict information in a clear and easy-to-understand manner. Readability of the text, simplicity of sound labels, and visibility of directional outputs must be provided. This makes sure that system outputs can be easily interpreted by users in real-time scenarios.\newline

\noindent
Fourth, audio processing standards are implemented to make sure that signals are properly analyzed. Audio is recorded by the system with the ReSpeaker microphone array in 16-bit PCM at a 16 kHz sampling rate. The speech recognition method is implemented with the help of Google Speech-to-Text API and LINEAR16 encoding. GCC-PHAT and TDOA methods are used to localize sound and the YAMNet model is used to recognize sounds. These techniques will guarantee effective and accurate sound processing.\newline

\noindent
Lastly, the performance of a system is measured in terms of set measures. These are sound localization error of less than 15 degrees, sound event detection accuracy above 90\%, response time under one second, transcription error of less than 15 percent and total weight of the system of less than 500 grams. These measures guarantee that the system works effectively and provides reliable support in real-world scenarios..

\subsection{Engineering Considerations}
\subsubsection{Relevant Ethical Aspects and Codes of Ethics}

The development of the Sound-Based Scene Descriptor is guided by the IEEE Code of Ethics~\cite{ieee_p78}, with a focus on public safety, technical honesty, and professional competence.

\paragraph{\textbf{IEEE Code 1 (Public Safety and Welfare):}}
The system is designed with safety as a primary objective, ensuring that critical environmental sounds (e.g., sirens or vehicle horns) are detected and localized as reliably as possible. Since incorrect directional feedback may introduce physical risk, the design prioritizes the All-Features fusion model to maximize robustness in real-world environments. Additionally, privacy is considered by performing core audio processing (feature extraction and localization) locally on-device. Only high-level outputs (e.g., detected sound labels and direction) are transmitted to the user interface, avoiding storage or transmission of raw audio data.

\paragraph{\textbf{IEEE Code 4 (Societal Impact and Public Understanding):}}
The system contributes to improving public understanding of emerging technologies by translating advanced AI methods (e.g., CNN-based sound classification, YAMNet, and GCC-PHAT localization) into a practical assistive application. The system integrates a custom web-based interface to visualize sound direction and transcribed speech in real time, enhancing usability and accessibility. The design process included consultation with domain specialists at the Sheikh Salem Al-Ali Al-Sabah Centre, ensuring that the system addresses real user needs and delivers meaningful societal impact.

\paragraph{\textbf{IEEE Code 5 (Honest and Realistic Claims):}}
The team maintains transparency in performance reporting. While near-perfect accuracy is achieved under controlled conditions (Scenario 1), the system is evaluated primarily on realistic, unseen environments (Scenario 2), where it achieves 88.05\% accuracy with an average localization error of 8.9°. This prevents overestimation and provides a truthful assessment of system readiness.

\paragraph{\textbf{IEEE Code 6 (Professional Competence):}}
All technical decisions were guided by empirical validation rather than assumptions. For example, the selection of a 16\,ms frame size was based on real-time deployment constraints of the ReSpeaker XVF3800 pipeline, ensuring consistency between training and inference. Hardware limitations were also explicitly considered, leading to a hybrid implementation where computationally intensive training is performed on GPU-capable systems, while real-time inference and visualization are deployed on the Raspberry Pi and connected interface.

\paragraph{\textbf{IEEE Code 7 (Fairness and Non-Discrimination):}}
The project promotes accessibility by supporting individuals with hearing impairments, enabling equal environmental awareness. To further ensure inclusivity, the system incorporates Arabic and Kuwaiti dialect speech-to-text capabilities, addressing a common limitation in assistive technologies that predominantly support English, and reducing barriers for non-English-speaking users within the local community.

\subsubsection{Impact of Proposed Solution}
The proposed system is designed with consideration of its broader impact across societal, economic, and environmental dimensions. This subsection evaluates how the system contributes to improving quality of life for hearing-impaired users, its cost-effectiveness relative to existing solutions, and its environmental footprint during operation.

\paragraph{Societal Impact:}
The proposed system enhances spatial awareness and situational understanding for deaf and hard-of-hearing users, improving independence and daily safety. By providing real-time identification and localization of environmental sounds, the system reduces reliance on external assistance and increases user confidence in navigating complex environments. The inclusion of Arabic and Kuwaiti dialect support (discussed under IEEE Code 7) further ensures accessibility for local communities. The design also aligns with Kuwait's Vision 2035 by supporting the integration of people with disabilities into society. User-centered feedback, obtained through consultation with specialists at the Sheikh Salem Al-Ali Al-Sabah Centre, emphasized the importance of a discreet wearable design, which helps reduce social stigma and encourages adoption.

\paragraph{Economic Impact:}
The system is designed to be cost-effective, with a total prototype cost of approximately 86~KD, as detailed in Section~\ref{sec:cost}. This is significantly lower than conventional assistive solutions, such as hearing aids and cochlear implants, which can cost several hundreds to thousands of Kuwaiti dinars.\newline

\noindent
The low cost is achieved through the use of off-the-shelf components, including the Raspberry Pi 5 and ReSpeaker 4-microphone array, ensuring scalability and ease of maintenance. Despite its low cost, the system integrates multiple functionalities—sound classification, speech-to-text, and sound source localization—providing greater value compared to existing solutions that offer limited features.

\paragraph{Environmental Impact:}
The system is optimized for low power consumption, operating at approximately 5 W on the Raspberry Pi 5, making it energy-efficient for continuous use. Its fully offline operation, as noted under IEEE Code 1, also eliminates dependence on cloud-based processing, reducing the environmental footprint associated with data centers and network infrastructure. Finally, the use of standard electronic modules supports responsible disposal and recycling practices as electronic waste.\newline

\noindent
Overall, the proposed solution demonstrates a balanced consideration of societal benefit, economic feasibility, and environmental responsibility, supporting its potential for real-world deployment.


\subsubsection{Alignment of proposed solution with the Engineering codes of Ethics and taking into consideration the impacts of the design}
This device was designed under specific constraints and standards to comply with engineering ethics and to take into consideration the potential impacts, while ensuring a high level of safety and privacy for users with hearing impairments. As engineers, our first priority during the design phase is the user’s safety. This is especially important because the device helps users understand their surroundings by converting sound into understandable information. The system provides alerts on the web interface in case of danger and identifies the direction of the sound source. This helps the user stay safe and react quickly. In addition to its physical design, the device is made suitable for everyday use. It is lightweight, which prevents it from restricting the user’s movement. Also, overheating was considered in the design to make the device safer for daily use.\newline

\noindent
Privacy is preserved by performing real-time audio analysis without storing or transmitting raw data. Additionally, system performance is reported transparently based on experimental evaluation under realistic conditions, acknowledging limitations such as reduced accuracy in noisy environments and potential latency due to network-dependent processing. From an impact perspective, the system enhances independence and accessibility for deaf and hard-of-hearing users, while remaining cost-effective through the use of off-the-shelf components. Environmental considerations are also addressed through energy-efficient operation and support for component reuse and responsible disposal.
\newline

\noindent
Generally, the device targets deaf and hard-of-hearing individuals, as it does not amplify sound but converts sound into visual and text information. It translates spoken conversation into text and shows the type and direction of sound. This solution has social, economic, and environmental impacts. Socially, it increases user safety and independence, providing sufficient support to help users rely on themselves and integrate smoothly into society. Economically, the device is more affordable than other devices on the market, in addition to offering useful technological features. Environmentally, the device is long-lasting, and its components can be reused, maintained, or upgraded instead of replacing the whole system.\newline

\noindent
However, some negative impacts exist, such as reduced performance in noisy environments, increased power consumption, limited battery life, possible false detection, and the presence of electronic components that require proper disposal. To reduce these negative impacts, preprocessing and noise reduction are used to improve performance in noisy environments. Also, Raspberry Pi was selected instead of a more expensive or heavier device to balance cost, weight, and performance. Finally, the system avoids storing audio to protect user privacy, and proper handling of electronic components should be considered to reduce electronic waste.

