\section{CONCLUSION AND FUTURE WORKS}

This project presented a wearable, non-prosthetic assistive system designed to enhance situational awareness for individuals with deafness or hearing impairments. Unlike conventional assistive technologies that focus on sound amplification, the proposed system transforms acoustic signals into meaningful semantic and spatial information through three integrated subsystems — sound source localization, environmental sound recognition, and real-time speech-to-text transcription — deployed on a Raspberry Pi 5 with a ReSpeaker XVF3800 four-microphone array and delivered through a web-based visual interface.\newline

\noindent
For sound source localization, a systematic tuning study on a 1D CNN was conducted, covering architecture width, optimizer selection, class balancing, RMS-based silence filtering, and feature ablation, followed by the development of a GRU model with a 32-frame temporal context window. The GRU achieved 99.19\% offline cross-recording accuracy and 90.7\% within-$\pm$15° real-time accuracy, matching the performance of the ReSpeaker's built-in hardware DOA estimator while remaining fully learnable and adaptable. Compared to related work — where~\cite{Tang2025} achieved high accuracy but was limited to five discrete angles,~\cite{Senaha2025} evaluated only a 150° arc from a single recording setup, and~\cite{Tan2025} provided only coarse four-direction output — the proposed system covers the full 360° with 15° angular resolution, demonstrating improved robustness and directional precision.\newline

\noindent
For environmental sound recognition, the YAMNet model achieved an estimated classification accuracy of 90\%–95\% under practical indoor conditions. High confidence values for speech and silence confirmed reliable differentiation between acoustic events. Source distance influenced prediction confidence, and minor misclassifications occurred only with low-confidence outputs, not affecting the primary function of notifying users about meaningful surrounding sounds. For speech-to-text, Google Speech-to-Text was selected based on comparative evaluation, achieving an overall recognition rate above 85\% for both Arabic (including Kuwaiti dialect) and English. Short utterances and keywords were transcribed faster and more accurately than longer sentences, and the system handled the Kuwaiti dialect reasonably well, though some spelling errors indicate room for further improvement.\newline

\noindent
The complete prototype was assembled at approximately 120.5 KD, well within the 400 KD budget constraint and significantly more cost-effective than comparable market solutions. Experimental investigations confirmed the feasibility of running all three subsystems simultaneously on an embedded platform, demonstrating that a low-cost, multi-modal assistive system can provide hearing-impaired users with real-time situational awareness, directional information, and live speech captions.

\paragraph{Future Works\\}
Building on the current system, the following directions are identified for further development:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Web interface vibration alerts:} The existing web-based interface will be extended to include software-driven vibration alerts for critical sound events such as alarms and sirens. This allows users accessing the system through a smartphone or tablet browser to receive haptic notifications directly on their device, without requiring any additional hardware.

    \item \textbf{AR lenses integration (optional):} As an alternative output channel, the system output can be integrated with AR lenses, enabling the user to view sound labels, directional arrows, and live speech captions without a separate screen. This would make the device fully wearable and self-contained, achieving the original design vision for users who prefer a hands-free experience.

    \item \textbf{Cross-environment generalization and accuracy improvement:} All training and testing were conducted in a single indoor environment. Future work will include data collection across multiple rooms, distances, and acoustic conditions to improve localization and recognition accuracy in diverse real-world settings, including noisy outdoor environments.

    \item \textbf{GRU fine-tuning and on-device adaptation:} Incorporating an online or few-shot adaptation mechanism will allow the GRU to fine-tune to a new acoustic environment with minimal data, further improving accuracy without requiring full retraining from scratch.

    \item \textbf{Speech-to-text improvement:} Recognition accuracy for Arabic, particularly for children's voices and longer sentences, requires further development. Fine-tuning on locally collected Arabic speech datasets and focusing on short warning phrases and keywords would improve both accuracy and response time.

    \item \textbf{Outdoor deployment and testing:} One of the system's defined performance requirements is reliable operation in both indoor and outdoor environments. All current experiments were conducted indoors; future work will include systematic outdoor testing across different settings such as streets, open spaces, and transportation environments. This will evaluate system robustness against wind noise, variable reverberation, and unpredictable acoustic conditions that are absent in controlled indoor setups.


    \item \textbf{Noise robustness and beamforming:} Incorporating beamforming or advanced spatial filtering at the signal conditioning stage could improve both localization and recognition in noisy environments, extending the system's reliable operating range.

    \item \textbf{User study with hearing-impaired individuals:} A formal usability study with hearing-impaired participants, including individuals from the Sheikh Salem Al-Ali Al-Sabah Centre, would provide essential user-centered feedback and validate the system's real-world benefit and acceptance.
\end{itemize}



